      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "as a shepherd divideth his sheep from the goats",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] “The sheep and goats are always seen together under the same shepherd and in company; yet they never trespass on the domain of each other.… When folded together at night they may always be seen gathered in distinct groups; and so, round the wells they appear instinctively to classify themselves apart, as they wait for the troughs to be filled.”—Tristram, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Natural History of the Bible",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", pp. 89, 90. The goat was not in evil repute in the East, as contrasted with the sheep; on the contrary, the he-goat was a symbol of dignity, so that the point of analogy is merely the separation between the sheep and the goats.",
        "children": []
      },
